Firstly, a homogeneous and stable aqueous dispersion (2.5 × 104 µg/L) was obtained by dissolving as-functionalized T-NS-CDs into HEPES buffer solutions (pH = 7.04, 10 mM), implying that the good dispersing ability. The buffer solution exhibits the excitation wavelength at 395 nm and the maximum emission located at 463 nm, coincided with the fluorescent spectra of NS-CDs, as represented in 
                           Fig. S4
                        . Furthermore, when the changes of excitation wavelength in the range of 355–455 nm, the fluorescence intensity displays increase first and then decrease, reaching the maximum excitation wavelength at 395 nm (
                           Fig. S5
                        ), demonstrating that the excitation-dependent photoluminescence is controlled by the surface states of CDs [41,42]. The CIE color coordinate (X, Y = 0.16, 0.19) provides compelling evidence that the fluorescence belongs to the blue fluorescence region (
                           Fig. S6
                        ), which is in accordance with the pictures of CDs solution under the excitation at 365 nm. Additionally, no obvious changes of emission intensity are perceived after 60-min irradiation with an interval of 5 min (
                           Fig. S7
                        ), representing the excellent photostability. Similarly, the fluorescent quenching efficiency is found to be inappreciable even at the presence of 1.0 M NaCl (
                           Fig. S8
                        ), confirming the insensitivity to high salt environment. Also, considering the protonation / deprotonation interactions of functional groups on CDs surface, the influence of various pH on fluorescent intensity in HEPES buffer solution was tested over a wide range of pH 2.0–13.0. As depicted in 
                           Fig. S9
                        , when pH value is less than 3.0 or more than 12.0, the dramatic decreases are found, while the changes of emission intensity could be negligible under a wide range of pH 4.0–11.0. Meanwhile, the emission intensity at 463 nm decreases dramatically in the presence of Hg2+ under a wide range of pH 5.0–11.0. Therefore, the following fluorescent titration were carried out in HEPES (pH = 7.04, 10 mM) buffer solution.

Given that the interconversion between T-Hg2+-T and DMSA-Hg2+ complex has happened by alternating addition of Hg2+ and DMSA, the reversibility of the CDs sensor was investigated. First of all, 50 µL Hg2+ solution (5.01 × 104 µg/L) was added to quench the fluorescence of T-NS-CDs, and then after the reaction was completed, 50 µL DMSA solution (4.55 × 104 µg/L) was employed to restore the fluorescence, and the reliability of the method was verified by repeating experiments in turn. It is found that this switching could be repeated more than 3 times, indicating that the “off–on” model is relatively stable (
                           Fig. S16
                        ).
